Explanation â€” how I derived the Operation Object for POST /v1/posts:

- Controller and action:
  - The request is handled by App\Http\Controllers\Api\V1\PostController@store (the store method). This is the POST /v1/posts endpoint.

- Request validation and accepted fields:
  - The PostsRequest (app/Http/Requests/Admin/PostsRequest.php) performs validation and prepares data. The store method calls $request->only(['title', 'content', 'posted_at', 'author_id', 'thumbnail_id']) when creating the Post model, so these are the request fields the endpoint accepts.
  - Validation rules show title and content are required, posted_at is required and must be a date, author_id is required and must exist (an integer id), thumbnail_id is nullable and must reference media,id when present. PostsRequest also sets slug in prepareForValidation, but store only uses the fields listed above to create the Post.

- Response shape:
  - The store method returns new PostResource(Post::create(...)). The PostResource (app/Http/Resources/Post.php) defines the JSON structure of a single post: id, title, slug, content, posted_at (ISO8601 string), author_id, comments_count (computed or provided), thumbnail_url and thumb_thumbnail_url (conditionally present if the post has a thumbnail). I used those fields in the response schema. Fields that are conditionally present (thumbnail_url, thumb_thumbnail_url) are represented as possibly null / optional.

- Error responses:
  - Validation failures from PostsRequest will produce HTTP 422 responses with a JSON body that typically contains "message" and "errors" keys (errors is an object mapping field names to arrays of messages).
  - Authorization via $this->authorize('store', Post::class) may cause a 403 Forbidden response. I included a minimal 403 response schema with a message.

- Chosen HTTP response code:
  - The successful creation response is represented as HTTP 201 Created with the JSON representation of the PostResource.

I included only fields that can be inferred from the provided controller, request, and resource code: request body fields, their types/requirements, response JSON fields, and the likely error responses. I did not invent unrelated operation metadata.

